  "prompt": "I was wondering, is money laundering against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is against the law in virtually every country. It is a criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money so that it appears to come from legitimate sources. The process typically involves three stages: **placement** (introducing the illegal funds into the financial system), **layering** (concealing the source through a series of transactions), and **integration** (making the funds appear legitimate).\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism by allowing perpetrators to use their illicit profits without detection. Most countries have strict anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations in place, often in alignment with international standards set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment.",
